.
Chewy=E2=80=99s stock spiked after Gill=E2=80=99s post last Thursday, jumpi=
ng from the prior day=E2=80=99s close of $29.15 to a high of $35.95 in midd=
ay trading, only to then sink back to around $29 by the time the market clo=
sed.
Gill=E2=80=99s filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, dated Ju=
ne 24 and made public Monday, shows that he owns 9 million shares in Chewy.=
 Gill checked a box on the filing noting that he is =E2=80=9Cnot a cat,=E2=
=80=9D a distinction he made to lawmakers in his 2021 congressional testimo=
ny in the GameStop saga.

Here's Keith Gill=E2=80=99s Schedule 13G, because Keith Gill is a 13G filer=
 now. Good for him. There is not actually a box on Schedule 13G labeled =E2=
=80=9CCheck the appropriate box to designate whether you are a cat,=E2=80=
=9D but you can kind of type whatever you want, and he did. Obviously it wi=
ll be funny if Chewy founder Ryan Cohen controls GameStop and GameStop =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0mascot? =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Keith Gill controls Chewy, but honestly =
not that funny. It feels like there are diminishing returns to all of this,=
 both as a matter of market impact and as a matter of comedy. But, sure, if=
 you have the magic ability to make=C2=A0a stock go up just by talking abou=
t it, that is intoxicating, and you=E2=80=99ll do what you can to hold onto=
 it.

 =20
   =20
      Chutzpah
   =20
 =20

Some US states have passed laws making it illegal for employers to discrimi=
nate against employees (or potential employees) based on their criminal rec=
ords. The natural arbitrage is:
=09Get a job.=09Steal from your employer.=09When you get fired, say =E2=80=
=9Cno, I have=C2=A0committed a crime, and you can=E2=80=99t discriminate ag=
ainst me based on my criminal record, so you can=E2=80=99t fire me.=E2=80=
=9D

This is not a good plan, because between Steps 2 and 3 you go to jail, but =
it is a very funny plan. Also =E2=80=94=C2=A0extremely not legal advice =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0it might work?

Two brothers found guilty of stealing scrap metal from the Oconomowoc Area =
School District have been fighting for eight years to keep their jobs with =
the district.=C2=A0
Their case is now headed to the Wisconsin Supreme Court.=C2=A0
Gregory and Jeff Cota were part of the school district=E2=80=99s grounds cr=
ew. An investigation in 2014 found the brothers, a supervisor and co-worker=
 kept more than $5,000 that was supposed to be turned over to the district =
after they recycled scrap metal, according to the lawsuit.
Police investigated the case. The Cotas were issued citations for municipal=
 theft.=C2=A0
The Cotas agreed to pay $500 restitution to the school district, and they w=
ere ultimately fired for theft in 2016.=C2=A0
In 2021, the state=E2=80=99s Labor and Industry Review Commission found the=
 Oconomowoc School District violated the Wisconsin Fair Employment Act=E2=
=80=99s prohibition against arrest record discrimination.=C2=A0

That was reversed on appeal, but it=E2=80=99s now before the state supreme =
court, so who knows. It=E2=80=99s possible that the rule is that, if you co=
mmit crimes at work, you can be fired=C2=A0or=C2=A0prosecuted, but not both=
.

 =20
   =20
      Chevron
   =20
 =20

It=E2=80=99s been a wild few days for the US Supreme Court, and I am not go=
ing to cover it in any depth, but I should note that the Court=C2=A0overrul=
ed Chevron last week, meaning that courts no longer have to defer to regula=
tory agencies=E2=80=99 interpretations of laws. I wrote last Thursday: =E2=
=80=9CI continue to think that there is a live possibility that, in the not=
 too distant future, the Supreme Court will rule that the SEC has no power =
to make rules, and all of its rules are invalid. But not today.=E2=80=9D Ki=
nd of Friday, though.
I have written around here about the US Securities and Exchange Commission=
=E2=80=99s=C2=A0regulatory agenda in the last few years =E2=80=94=C2=A0thin=
gs like its new climate disclosure rules=C2=A0or swaps disclosure rules=C2=
=A0or private funds rules =E2=80=94=C2=A0and I kind of wish I hadn=E2=80=99=
t.=C2=A0
Anyway, here=E2=80=99s Noah Feldman at Bloomberg Opinion on Chevron. Here=
=E2=80=99s Rachel Barkow. Today I think the Supreme Court ruled that the pr=
esident can order anyone murdered without consequence? Which really seems l=
ike a more expansive regulatory power than interpreting statutes. We have f=
un around here, thinking about the rules and how they work and what sorts o=
f things=C2=A0you can construct, if you are clever, to take advantage of th=
e rules. I find myself already missing that sort of fun. I worry=C2=A0that =
there are no rules anymore.

