  [1] Most typically, this is a problem of =E2=80=9C
authorized shares=E2=80=9D: The certificate of incorporation (the charter) =
says =E2=80=9Cthe company can issue up to 100 million shares of common stoc=
k,=E2=80=9D or whatever, and it has 99.97 million shares outstanding and wa=
nts to sell another 20 million shares to raise money.=20


  [2] Often it takes the form of =E2=80=9Cblank check preferred stock.=E2=
=80=9D Typically a corporate charter that says =E2=80=9Cthe company can iss=
ue up to 100 million shares of common stock=E2=80=9D will go on to say =E2=
=80=9Cand up to 20 million shares of preferred stock, which can have whatev=
er terms the board of directors wants.=E2=80=9D If the charter authorizes t=
he board to issue preferred stock and set whatever terms it wants (a =E2=80=
=9Cblank check=E2=80=9D for the board), it can issue preferred stock with t=
erms that mirror the common. So you issue, like, 1 million shares of new pr=
eferred stock, and the terms of the preferred stock are (1) each share is e=
ntitled to the same economic rights (dividends, etc.) as 20 common shares, =
(2) each share gets to vote with the common stock and has 20 votes and (3) =
the company will, at the next chance it gets, ask its shareholders to vote =
to authorize more shares, and if and when the shareholders approve, each sh=
are of preferred stock will automatically convert into 20 shares of common =
stock. And typically you can build in some protections for the buyer: It bu=
ys the preferred shares at a discount to the price of real shares, the pref=
erred shares get to vote along with the regular shares, the preferred share=
s get any dividends that the regular shares get, if the preferred shares do=
n=E2=80=99t flip into real shares within some reasonable time, there=E2=80=
=99s some penalty (the company has to pay back the money, or pay interest),=
 etc. But for our purposes here, the preferred shares are a class of shares=
 that function like IOUs for future common shares.


  [3] It briefly dipped to $9.90 on the afternoon of June 21; not sure if t=
hat was Liqueous=E2=80=99s selling or what. Since last Monday it never got =
below $10.17.


  [4] Several readers emailed me about it, many of them complaining that Li=
queous=E2=80=99s sales might be *insider trading*: Liqueous knew the materi=
al facts about this deal, but the market didn=E2=80=99t, and it apparently =
sold the stock while everyone else was unaware. This seems plausible to me,=
 but not the biggest problem!


