<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Every so often a company needs to sell stock, =
but it doesn=E2=80=99t have any stock to sell. There is some restriction in=
 its corporate charter saying that it can=E2=80=99t issue any more stock,<a=
 class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpa=
rent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0but it=C2=A0needs money, there are willing buyers, and there=E2=
=80=99s a deal to be done, if only there were=C2=A0any shares of stock left=
. It is a frustrating problem. =E2=80=9CStock=E2=80=9D is not a real thing;=
 stock is=C2=A0just a way=C2=A0to account for fractional ownership of the c=
ompany, and in some sense the company can always create more. It=E2=80=99s =
just that the corporate charter does not currently allow it to.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What can it do? There are two main approaches:=
</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Most of the time, the restriction in =
the charter can be changed by a shareholder vote. So the company can go ask=
 the shareholders to let it issue more stock, and hold a vote, and if it wi=
ns the vote it can sell more shares. This completely solves the problem. Bu=
t it takes time: If the company needs money now, waiting months to get a sh=
areholder vote is a problem. Also sometimes the shareholders vote no, becau=
se they don=E2=80=99t like dilution, or they don=E2=80=99t vote at all, bec=
ause they are retail investors who tend not to vote.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Or the company can sell, not <em>stock</em>, but I=
OUs for stock, promises to issue stock later. The company has a buyer who w=
ill pay $50 million for 10 million new shares of stock, and the company thi=
nks that=E2=80=99s a good price and wants to act now, but it has no shares =
left. So it goes to the buyer and says =E2=80=9Clook, we will=C2=A0<em>even=
tually=C2=A0</em>get 10 million new shares. We=E2=80=99ll hold a shareholde=
r vote, as many times as necessary to get approval. But that takes time, an=
d we want to do this trade now. So why don=E2=80=99t you give us the $50 mi=
llion now, and we=E2=80=99ll give you a contract saying that, when we=C2=A0=
<em>can=C2=A0</em>give you 10 million shares, we will.=E2=80=9D</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously the second approach creates some ris=
k for the buyer =E2=80=94=C2=A0what if it never gets the shares? =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0but it does happen.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important=
; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
