<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">24-hour trading</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have thought sometimes that financial market=
s should be divided into two clearly demarcated regimes, which I once calle=
d <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35921520.194416/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDQtMDkvYS1=
tZW1lLXN0b2NrLWZvci1wcml2YXRlLWNvbXBhbmllcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzAxMjRfTU9ORVlTVF=
VGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA3M=
DEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf24e98f8" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">the Nice Market and the Fun Market</a>. The Nice Market has rules, and t=
he rules aim to achieve fairness, informative asset prices and efficient ca=
pital formation. The Fun Market has fewer rules, and it aims to achieve fun=
. The Nice Market, like all financial markets, tolerates a certain amount o=
f speculation, because speculation can be good for price efficiency and liq=
uidity. The Fun Market mostly encourages gambling.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then if you want fairness and efficient pr=
icing =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you are a buy-and-hold index investor looking to in=
vest your retirement funds in equity claims on the economy at prices reflec=
ting the market=E2=80=99s sense of the present value of future cash flows =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0you invest in the Nice Market. And if you want to gamble, yo=
u invest in the Fun Market.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This suggestion is not=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em=
>real, because financial markets are interconnected, and inevitably some of=
 the fun had in the Fun Market would bleed back into the Nice Market. And s=
ome people looking for the Nice Market would inevitably stumble into the Fu=
n one and have, you know, too much fun. (I originally proposed this for=C2=
=A0<em>crypto</em>, because crypto markets are just=C2=A0<em>less=C2=A0</em=
>interconnected than real ones. Who cares about price efficiency and capita=
l formation in a memecoin?)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still it is a useful thought experiment. Consi=
der segmenting the stock market by=C2=A0<em>time</em>. It=E2=80=99s so intu=
itive:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you are buying large-cap US stocks=
 at the 4 p.m. closing auction, when big index funds do their trades to get=
 maximum liquidity and match the =E2=80=9Cofficial=E2=80=9D price of the da=
y, you are=C2=A0<em>clearly=C2=A0</em>looking for the Nice Market, and that=
=E2=80=99s what you should get. If the closing auction is very volatile, or=
 manipulated, that would be self-evidently bad: Zillions=C2=A0of dollars of=
 indexed retirement savings would be getting inaccurate prices.</li>=09<li =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you are buying small-cap US stocks at 3=C2=
=A0a.m.,=C2=A0<em>you do not care about price efficiency or capital formati=
on</em>. Everyone who cares about price efficiency or capital formation is =
in bed. The market at 3 a.m. is the Fun Market. You do not need me to tell =
you this, or=C2=A0a regulator or your broker. It is intuitively obvious tha=
t if you=E2=80=99re on your computer speculating on stocks at 3 a.m.,=C2=A0=
<em>you are gambling</em>.=C2=A0</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Lu Wang and Katheri=
ne Doherty have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35=
921520.194416/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtM=
DYtMzAvd2hlbi1kby1tYXJrZXRzLWNsb3NlLTI0LWhvdXItc3RvY2stdHJhZGluZy1wdXNoLXNw=
b29rcy13YWxsLXN0cmVldD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzAxMjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWV=
tYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA3MDEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW=
1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9959ad52" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a story today on t=
he rise of 24-hour retail trading</a>, which features a lot of complaints o=
f the form =E2=80=9Cthe market at 3 a.m. is not Nice=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re only going to have trou=
ble in the middle of the night when things are so illiquid,=E2=80=9D says J=
oseph Saluzzi, co-head of equity trading at Themis Trading LLC.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A market veteran of more than three decades, S=
aluzzi has been perturbed by a handful of huge moves at unexpected times re=
cently, like a 20% surge in GameStop Corp. on a Sunday evening in June. His=
 big fear is that someone could take advantage of slow overnight trading to=
 create momentum in a share, pushing it higher for a quick profit. =E2=80=
=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A Bloomberg Intelligence analysis showed that =
nearly three-quarters of stock volume on Blue Ocean [<em>Technologies LLC, =
an alternative trading system=C2=A0for overnight trading</em>] was in illiq=
uid names, or those with a spread between bid and ask price of over 30 basi=
s points. At major alternative trading venues which focus on regular hours,=
 that cohort accounts for an average of just 16.6% of activity.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CYou might incur extra spreads=E2=80=
=9D when trading overnight, Sanders at Interactive Brokers says. =E2=80=9CP=
eople should do their homework and understand what the spread is during reg=
ular trading hours and compare it to overnight and decide if it's worth it.=
=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This just strikes me as a complete non-problem=
. If you have no view on price and just want to buy stocks at whatever pric=
e reflects an efficient market=E2=80=99s view of their value, you do that d=
uring the trading day, or at the closing auction, and you will get tight bi=
d-ask spreads. If you are trading at 3 a.m., you=C2=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>vo=
latility. You=C2=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>the possibility that stock prices are=
 20% too high, or 20% too low: That=E2=80=99s how you make money. I mean, o=
bviously: That=E2=80=99s how you lose money. But still. You want stocks to =
trade at the wrong price, because that=E2=80=99s what makes the game fun an=
d risky and potentially rewarding. If stocks trade at the right prices, you=
 can=E2=80=99t make any money, and that=E2=80=99s boring; save that for the=
 Nice Market during daylight.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there are other complaints, for which I ha=
ve more sympathy, of the form =E2=80=9Cyes obviously the 3 a.m. market is F=
un, but the Fun Market inevitably bleeds into the Nice Market and vice vers=
a=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Proponents of non-stop trading poi=
nt out that issues like illiquidity and wide spreads will naturally lesson =
as overnight volumes increase. In a kind of virtuous circle, they expect ri=
sing activity will also pave the way for larger trade sizes and hence more =
institutional involvement, further improving market depth and breadth.</p><=
/blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes right if the stock market is really open 2=
4 hours a day then some institutions will trade at 3 a.m. to get an edge an=
d to react to news, and then other institutions will have to, and then ever=
yone will be awake all the time and that seems exhausting:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A market that never sleeps could c=
reate mental hazards for anyone who feels pressured to constantly monitor m=
oves or reactively adjust positions, according to Malcolm Polley, chief mar=
ket strategist at Stratos Investment Management.</p></blockquote>
